'''Telperion''' was the elder of the [[Two Trees of Valinor]], called the '''White Tree''', which shed silver light on the domain of the [[Valar]]. His leaves were of dark green, shining silver beneath, and his boughs were decked with brilliant flowers that shed a rain of silver dew, which was collected as a source of water and of light.<ref name=Days>{{S|Days}}</ref>

==History==
Telperion was the elder of the Two Trees, and created by the [[Vala]] [[Yavanna]]. It bloomed during the first part of the Valian day, followed by [[Laurelin]]. It endured throughout the [[Years of the Trees]], but came to an end in the dreadful [[Darkening of Valinor]]. 

However one of Telperion's flowers survived the Darkening, and was set aloft by the Valar; this was the light of the [[Moon]], carried by [[Tilion]] the [[Maia]].<ref>{{S|11}}</ref>

In the [[First Age]], [[Turgon]] made images of the Two Trees that stood in his court of [[Gondolin]], and the one made in memory of Telperion was [[Belthil]].<ref>{{S|15}}</ref>

===Telperion's descendants===
Even though the elder tree did not survive, he was not the last of the White Trees. Because the Elves that first came to Valinor especially loved Telperion, Yavanna made a second tree like it to stand in the city of [[Tirion]] where the [[Vanyar]] and [[Noldor]] dwelt together at first. This tree, named ''[[Galathilion]]'', was identical to Telperion except that it gave no light of its own. It had many seedlings, one of which was [[Celeborn (White Tree)|Celeborn]] on the isle of [[Tol Eressëa]].<ref>{{S|5}}</ref>

In the [[Second Age]], a seedling of Celeborn was brought as a gift to the [[Númenoreans]] — that was [[Nimloth of Númenor|Nimloth]], the White Tree of [[Númenor]]. It lasted through the vast majority of the realm's duration, but when [[Sauron]] took control of the island he had king [[Ar-Pharazôn]] chop it down. Fortunately, [[Isildur]] managed to save a single fruit of that tree. Of this fruit later came the [[White Tree of Gondor]].<ref>{{S|Akallabeth}}</ref>

==Etymology==
''Telperion'' comes from the root ''[[telepi]]''/''[[telpë]]'' ("silver").<ref>{{S|Appendix}} ''celeb-''</ref> The exact etymology of the ending ''-rion'' is not clear. Latter elements may include ''[[rî]]'' ("garland, wreath"),<ref>{{S|Appendix}}kal-</ref> and/or ''ere'' ("the one" or "first")<ref>{{webcite|website=[https://eldamo.org Eldamo]|articleurl=https://eldamo.org/content/words/word-3983103205.html|articlename=ereb|accessed=20 August 2020}}</ref><ref>{{webcite|website=[https://eldamo.org Eldamo]|articleurl=https://eldamo.org/content/words/word-3981134445.html|articlename=ereg|accessed=20 August 2020}}</ref> along with the suffix ''-on'' or ''-ion''.

The [[Quenya]] form was actually ''Tyelperion'' but Quenya adopted ''[[telpë]]'' from [[Telerin]].<ref>{{UT|6e}}, p. 266</ref>

==Other names==
Another [[Quenya]] name for Telperion was '''''Silpion'''''.<ref>{{MR|P2c}}, p. 59 (commentary to §5)</ref> It is derived from the root [[SIL]] (shine (with white or silver light))"<ref>{{S|Appendix}}, ''sil-''</ref> or from the extended root [[SILIP]],<ref name="SILIP">{{LR|Etymologies}}, entry "SIL"</ref> and the suffix ''-ion''.<ref>https://eldamo.org/content/words/word-4167656007.html?neo</ref> It was sometimes glossed the "White Tree of Valinor",<ref name="SILIP"/> or simply the "White Tree".

'''''Ninquelótë''''' was a [[Quenya]] title of Telperion.<ref name=Days/> ''Ninquelótë'' means "White Flower" or (perhaps more likely in this context) "White Blossom". The [[Sindarin]] equivalent of this Quenya name was ''[[Nimloth of Númenor|Nimloth]]'', and indeed that name was inherited by the White Tree that grew in the [[King's Court]] of [[Númenor]].

'''''Ibrīniðilpathānezel''''' was the name in [[Valarin]] of Telperion.<ref>{{WJ|AD1}}, p. 401</ref>

In early writings of [[J.R.R. Tolkien|Tolkien]] Telperion's names were '''''Silpion''''', '''''Bansil''''' and '''''Belthil'''''.{{fact}}

